concept.explanation:
## Why it matters

Imagine one service in your system suddenly starts queuing requests, consuming all threads or DB connections. Without isolation, that overload spreads — requests pile up, latencies spike, and the entire system degrades. The *Bulkhead pattern* prevents this by partitioning resources so a single noisy neighbor can't crash the building.

## Analogy — Ship compartments and apartment buildings

- *Ship bulkheads*: watertight compartments stop one breach from sinking the whole ship.
- *Apartment building*: if one flat has a power surge it shouldn't blow fuses for the entire building — isolating circuits keeps others powered.

Those are the same idea: create boundaries that contain failure.

## How it works (high level)

- Split capacity (threads, connection pools, semaphores, worker queues) into *isolated pools* for different callers or request types.
- If a pool is saturated, requests for that partition get rejected/queued/fallback, while other partitions keep serving.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  ClientA[Client A]
  ClientB[Client B]
  Gateway[API Gateway / Router]
  subgraph Bulkheads
    BH1[Pool A]\n(maxConcurrent=10)
    BH2[Pool B]\n(maxConcurrent=20)
  end
  DB[Downstream Database]

  ClientA -->|req type A| Gateway --> BH1 --> DB
  ClientB -->|req type B| Gateway --> BH2 --> DB
  BH1 -->|saturated| Gateway -.->|reject/fallback| ClientA

  classDef sat fill:#ffdddd,stroke:#ff4444;
  class BH1 sat
```

## Types of bulkheads

- **Thread-pool / worker-pool bulkhead**: dedicate threads/workers per subsystem or request class. Good when tasks block CPU or threads.
- **Semaphore (non-blocking) bulkhead**: limit concurrent calls using a semaphore; cheap, doesn't allocate threads.
- **Connection-pool bulkhead**: per-caller DB/API connection limits so one caller can't exhaust connections.

## BEFORE / AFTER (comparison)

| Scenario | Before (No Bulkhead) | After (With Bulkhead) |
|----------|----------------------|------------------------|
| One upstream client floods | Flood consumes all worker threads and DB connections → system-wide high latency and errors | Client's partition is throttled/failed quickly; other clients continue normally |
| Downstream dependency slow | All requests block waiting on slow dependency → request queue grows into OOM | Only the partition(s) that rely on that dependency are affected; other partitions stay healthy |
| Operational visibility | Hard to see which caller caused overload | Clear metrics per bulkhead: saturation, rejects, queue depth |

## Example: Java + Resilience4j (semaphore bulkhead)

```java
import io.github.resilience4j.bulkhead.annotation.Bulkhead;

// Apply per endpoint or service
@Bulkhead(name = "payments", type = Bulkhead.Type.SEMAPHORE, maxConcurrentCalls = 10)
public Mono<Response> processPayment(Request req) {
  // limited to 10 concurrent calls for payments
}
```

- When more than 10 concurrent calls arrive, further calls fail fast (or hit a configured fallback) rather than tying up threads.

## Example: Node.js simple semaphore-based bulkhead

```js
const Semaphore = (max) => {
  let current = 0;
  return async (fn) => {
    if (current >= max) throw new Error('bulkhead_rejected');
    current++;
    try { return await fn(); }
    finally { current--; }
  }
};

const paymentsBulkhead = Semaphore(5);

// usage
app.post('/payments', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const result = await paymentsBulkhead(() => processPayment(req.body));
    res.json(result);
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(503).json({ error: 'service busy' });
  }
});
```

## When to use it

- You have mixed workloads (heavy background jobs + low-latency APIs) that should not interfere with each other.
- A small set of callers or endpoints are allowed to consume bursty resources; you want to protect others.
- Downstream dependencies can fail or slow down and you must contain their impact.

## Common pitfalls

- *Too small pools*: causing unnecessary rejections and reduced throughput. Size conservatively and monitor.
- *Head-of-line blocking elsewhere*: if a global queue or gateway sits before per-bulkhead pools, you might still get blocking — place isolations as close to the consuming resource as possible.
- *Unbalanced partitions*: giving too much capacity to low-priority services can starve critical ones. Map partitions to business priorities.
- *Silent failures*: rejected requests must have clear, actionable fallbacks (error pages, retries with backoff, queuing) — otherwise you just hide errors.
- *Not instrumented*: without per-bulkhead metrics you won't know if you're throttling important traffic.

## Monitoring, metrics & sizing

Track these metrics per bulkhead:
- concurrent_calls (current)
- max_concurrent_calls (limit)
- available_permits / queue_depth
- rejected_calls (rate)
- latency of accepted calls

Sizing approach:
1. Start with a conservative limit (e.g., half of observed peak concurrency for that path).
2. Run load tests, observe rejected rate and latency.
3. Adjust limits by business priority and downstream capacity.

## Quick checklist before rolling out

- [ ] Decide partition keys (by endpoint, caller, priority)
- [ ] Choose implementation: thread pool, semaphore, or connection pool per partition
- [ ] Implement fast-failure and meaningful fallback paths
- [ ] Add per-bulkhead metrics and alerts
- [ ] Load-test and iterate on sizing

## TL;DR

Bulkheads give you fault isolation: degrade part of the system gracefully instead of risking total failure. They are simple but powerful — pair them with circuit breakers, timeouts, and good observability to build robust systems.

